///////////////////// function pointer passed as argument ////////////////////////
#include<stdio.h>
int fun(int (*)());
int main()
{
    fun(main);
    printf("Hi\n");
    return 0;
}
int fun(int (*p)())
{
    printf("Hello\n");
    return 0;
}
//////////////////

🧠 1️⃣ Understanding function pointer parameter
int fun(int (*p)());

👉 fun takes a function pointer as argument
👉 That pointer refers to a function returning int

So inside fun, p can point to any function like:

main
add
any function returning int
🧠 2️⃣ What is passed?
fun(main);

👉 main is passed as a function pointer

Equivalent to:

fun(&main);

So:

p → main
🧠 3️⃣ Inside function fun
int fun(int (*p)())
{
    printf("Hello\n");
    return 0;
}

👉 It does NOT use p at all
👉 It just prints:

Hello
🧠 4️⃣ Back to main

After returning from fun:
printf("Hi\n");

prints:
Hi

🖨 5️⃣ Final Output
Hello
Hi
🧠 6️⃣ Important Observation

Even though you passed:

fun(main);

👉 main() is NOT called inside fun

Because you never used:

p();   // missing
🔥 7️⃣ If we modify the code
int fun(int (*p)())
{
    printf("Hello\n");
    p();   // calling main again
    return 0;
}

👉 This will cause:

infinite recursion
main → fun → main → fun → ...
🧠 8️⃣ Function Pointer Concept
main is a function
main can decay to a pointer

So:
main == &main
